			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I've just done a bit of testing in Visual2C02, and it appears to fetch the tile scanline as if the sprite were infinitely tall and repeated vertically. Since secondary OAM gets prefilled with all 0xFFs, the tile number would always be 0xFF and the Y coordinate would also be 0xFF, and the vertical flip flag would also be set, so you'd get something like this for 8x8 sprites:<br /><br />Scanline 0: xFF6<br />Scanline 1: xFF5<br />Scanline 2: xFF4<br />Scanline 3: xFF3<br />Scanline 4: xFF2<br />Scanline 5: xFF1<br />Scanline 6: xFF0<br />Scanline 7: xFF7<br />Scanline 8: xFF6<br />etc. (where x is 0 or 1 depending on the sprite pattern table selected)<br /><br />For 8x16 sprites, you'd probably get something like this:<br /><br />Scanline 0: 1FF6<br />Scanline 1: 1FF5<br />Scanline 2: 1FF4<br />Scanline 3: 1FF3<br />Scanline 4: 1FF2<br />Scanline 5: 1FF1<br />Scanline 6: 1FF0<br />Scanline 7: 1FE7<br />Scanline 8: 1FE6<br />Scanline 9: 1FE5<br />Scanline 10: 1FE4<br />Scanline 11: 1FE3<br />Scanline 12: 1FE2<br />Scanline 13: 1FE1<br />Scanline 14: 1FE0<br />Scanline 15: 1FF7<br />etc.<br /><br />Note that in the actual Visual2C02, the vertical flip flag appears to be somewhat glitchy and gets forcibly cleared by some transistors flipping in the wrong order.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Quietust, QMT Productions
<br />P.S. If you don't get this note, let me know and I'll write you another.</div>
